.TH "tryto" "1" 
.SH NAME
tryto \- tries to run a command limited by a timeout or number of tries,
can be used to run as svlogd(8) processor.
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]tryto\f[R] [\-pPv] [\-t \f[I]sec\f[R]] [\-k \f[I]ksec\f[R]] [\-n
\f[I]tries\f[R]] \f[I]prog\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[I]prog\f[R] consist of one or more arguments.
.PP
\f[B]tryto\f[R] runs and watches \f[I]prog\f[R], feeding its standard
input to \f[I]prog\f[R]\[aq]s standard input.
If \f[I]prog\f[R] exits with a return code other then 0, \f[B]tryto\f[R]
runs \f[I]prog\f[R] again after sleeping one second.
.PP
If the number of retries reaches the maximal number of \f[I]tries\f[R],
\f[B]tryto\f[R] prints an error message and gives up.
.PP
If the timeout \f[I]sec\f[R] seconds is reached and \f[I]prog\f[R] is
still running, \f[B]tryto\f[R] sends a TERM signal to \f[I]prog\f[R],
waits \f[I]ksec\f[R] seconds for \f[I]prog\f[R] to terminate, then sends
a KILL signal if \f[I]prog\f[R] still is there, and exits as soon as
possible.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-t\f[R] \f[I]sec\f[R]
timeout.
Set the timeout to send TERM to \f[I]prog\f[R] to \f[I]sec\f[R] seconds.
Default is 180.
.TP
\f[B]\-k\f[R] \f[I]ksec\f[R]
kill timeout.
Set the timeout to send KILL to \f[I]prog\f[R] to \f[I]ksec\f[R]
seconds.
Default is 5.
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R] \f[I]tries\f[R]
Set the maximal number of tries to \f[I]tries\f[R].
If \f[I]prog\f[R] exited with a return code other that 0,
\f[B]tryto\f[R] tries to rewind standard input to the beginning using
\f[B]lseek\f[R](2) before starting \f[I]prog\f[R] again.
Default is 5.
.TP
\f[B]\-p\f[R]
processor.
Use this option if you run \f[B]tryto\f[R] as a \f[B]svlogd\f[R](8)
processor (see below).
.TP
\f[B]\-P\f[R]
process group.
Run \f[I]prog\f[R] in a new session and process group, and send signals
on timeout to \f[I]prog\f[R]\[aq]s process group instead of its pid.
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R]
verbose.
Print verbose messages to standard error.
.SH PROCESSOR
If \f[B]tryto\f[R] sees the \f[B]\-p\f[R] option, \f[B]tryto\f[R] runs
as a \f[B]svlogd\f[R](8) or \f[B]multilog\f[R](8) processor, making use
of filedescriptors 4 and 5:
.PP
Before starting \f[I]prog\f[R], \f[B]tryto\f[R] moves the filedescriptor
5 to 2, so all error messages from \f[B]tryto\f[R] and \f[I]prog\f[R]
will be saved in \f[B]svlogd\f[R](8)\[aq]s \f[I]state\f[R] to be
processed on the next run of \f[B]tryto\f[R] \f[B]\-p\f[R].
.PP
After starting \f[I]prog\f[R], \f[B]tryto\f[R] first feeds all data it
reads from filedescriptor 4 into \f[I]prog\f[R]\[aq]s standard input,
then all data from filedescriptor 0.
.PP
If \f[I]prog\f[R] fails by timeout \f[I]sec\f[R] seconds or maximal
number of \f[I]tries\f[R], \f[B]tryto\f[R] prints all data from standard
input to standard output, an error message to standard error, and exits
with 0.
.SH EXIT CODES
If \f[B]tryto\f[R] itself fails, it returns 111.
.PP
If \f[B]tryto\f[R] runs as a \f[B]svlogd\f[R](8) processor,
\f[B]tryto\f[R] returns 0 in all other cases.
.PP
If \f[I]prog\f[R] was run successfully, \f[B]tryto\f[R] returns 0.
.PP
If \f[I]prog\f[R] failed by timeout, \f[B]tryto\f[R] returns 100.
.PP
If \f[I]prog\f[R] failed by maximal number of \f[I]tries\f[R],
\f[B]tryto\f[R] returns the last return code from \f[I]prog\f[R].
.SH SEE ALSO
socklog(8), uncat(1), svlogd(8), multilog(8), lseek(2)
.PP
